{"parse":{"title":"coach","pageid":43970,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Coach}}\n==English==\n{{multiple images\n|direction = vertical\n|image1 = InterCity double decker.jpg\n|caption1 = A double-decker '''coach'''\n|image2 = Blue Train coach (8668442433).jpg\n|caption2 = The '''coach''' of a train\n|image3 = Imperial Palace Tokyo Ambassador on Kyuden Totei Plaza.JPG\n|caption3 = A horse-drawn '''coach''' in Japan\n|image4 = Tennis coach Duhok teaches backhand.jpg\n|caption4 = A tennis '''coach''' during a lesson\n}}\n\n===Etymology===\nBorrowed from {{bor|en|frm|coche}}, from {{der|en|de|Kutsche}}, from {{der|en|hu|kocsi}}. According to historians, the coach was named after the small Hungarian town of {{m|hu|Kocs}}, which made a livelihood from [[cart]] building and transport between Vienna and Budapest.\n\nThe meaning “instructor/trainer” is from Oxford University slang (c. 1830) for a “tutor” who “carries” one through an exam; the athletic sense is from 1861.<ref>{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/kəʊtʃ/|[kʰəʊ̯tʃ]|a=UK}}\n* {{IPA|en|/koʊt͡ʃ/|[kʰoʊ̯t͡ʃ]|a=US}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-coach.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{audio|en|EN-AU ck1 coach.ogg|a=AU}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-coach.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{rhymes|en|əʊtʃ|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A wheeled vehicle, generally pulled by a horse.\n#: {{syn|en|carriage}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=12 Feb 89|volume=16|number=30|journal=Gay Community News|page=9|title=A Night At The Opera|author=Jennifer Justice|text=I have a '''coach''' waiting. During intermission, would you consent to accompany me for a cooling ride around the city?}}\n# {{lb|en|rail|UK|Australia}} A [[passenger]] [[car]], either drawn by a [[locomotive]] or part of a [[multiple unit]].\n#: {{syn|en|carriage}}\n# {{senseid|en|trainer}} {{lb|en|originally|Oxford University|_|slang}} A [[trainer]] or [[instructor]].\n#: {{ux|en|football '''coach'''}}\n#: {{ux|en|spelling '''coach'''}}\n#: {{ux|en|public '''coach'''}}\n#: {{ux|en|horseriding '''coach'''}}\n#: {{ux|en|politics '''coach'''}}\n# {{lb|en|British|Australia}} A long-distance, or privately hired, [[bus]].\n# {{lb|en|nautical}} The forward part of the [[cabin]] space under the [[poop deck]] of a [[sailing ship]]; the fore-cabin under the [[quarter deck]].\n#* {{RQ:Pepys Diary|I|3 May 1660\n|passage=The commanders all came on board and the council sat in the '''coach'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|chiefly|US}} The part of a [[commercial]] [[passenger]] [[airplane]] or train reserved for those paying the lower standard [[fare]]s; the [[economy]] section.\n#: {{ux|en|We couldn't afford the good tickets, so we spent the flight crammed in '''coach'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|chiefly|US}} The lower-fare service whose passengers sit in this part of the airplane or train; [[economy class]].\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|en|accommodation coach|baby coach|coach bolt|coach box|coach gun|coach horn|coach up|coach-office|devil's coach-horse|drive a coach and horses through|get-back coach|glass coach|motor coach|motor-coach|quiet coach|rural coach|stage-coach|who's robbing this coach\n|autocoach|coach inn|dating coach|drive a coach and six through\n|camping coach\n|coach and horses|coach killer\n|coachbuilder\n|coachbuilding\n|coach-built,coachbuilt\n|coach dog\n|coach driver\n|coacher\n|coachhood\n|coach horse\n|coach lamp\n|coachman\n|coachmaster\n|coach roof\n|coach screw\n|[[coachwhip]] ({{taxfmt|Fouquieria splendens|species}})\n|coachwork\n|head coach\n|life coach\n|lozenge coach\n|roach coach\n|slip coach\n|slowcoach\n|slumbercoach,slumber coach\n|stagecoach\n|aircoach\n|coachbox|coach and four|coachdog\n|coachfellow\n|coachful\n|coachhorse\n|coachless|coach house\n|coachlet\n|coachlike\n|coachline\n|coachload\n|coachmaker\n|coachmaking\n|coachmark\n|coachmate\n|coachsmith\n|coachspeak\n|coachstand\n|coachwheel\n|coachwoman\n|coachwood\n|coachwright\n|coachyard\n|daycoach\n|encoach\n|mailcoach\n|motorcoach\n|supercoach\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|coachee}}<!--carriage-->\n\n====Descendants====\n{{top3}}\n* {{desc|cs|kouč|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|da|coach|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|nl|coach|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|fr|coach|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|de|Coach|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|it|coach|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ja|コーチ|tr=kōchi|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ko|코치|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ms|koc|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|pl|coach|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|pt|coach|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|es|coach|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|sw|kocha|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|sv|coach|bor=1}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top-also|wheeled vehicle drawn by horse power|carriage}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|կառք}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|паво́зка|f}}, {{t+|be|воз|m}}, {{t|be|карэ́та|f}}, {{t|be|экіпа́ж|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|по́щенска кола́|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|馬車|tr=mǎchē}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|kočár|m}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|personvogn|c}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|koets|c}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|ĉaro}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|vaunut}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|coche|m}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Kutsche|f}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|πούλμαν|n}}\n* Gujarati: {{t|gu|કોચ|n}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|hintó}}, {{t+|hu|kocsi}}, {{t+|hu|szekér}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|cóiste|m}}, {{t|ga|carráiste|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|carrozza|f}}, {{t+|it|vettura|f}}, {{t+|it|diligenza|f}}, {{t+|it|cocchio|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|馬車|tr=ばしゃ, basha}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|마차(馬車)}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+|kmr|erebe|f}}, {{t+|kmr|erebane|f}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|carrūca|f}}, {{t|la|raeda|f}}\n* Latvian: {{t+|lv|kariete|f}}, {{t+|lv|rati|m-p}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|кочија|f}}\n* Malay: {{t|ms|koc}}, {{t+|ms|gerabak}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|koti}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|cârrosse|f}}\n* Persian:\n*: Iranian Persian: {{t+|fa-ira|کالِسْکِه}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|powóz|m}}, {{t+|pl|kareta|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|coche|m}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|trăsură|f}}, {{t+|ro|caleașcă|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|пово́зка|f}}, {{t+|ru|каре́та|f}}, {{t+|ru|коля́ска|f}}, {{t+|ru|экипа́ж|m}}, {{t+|ru|дилижа́нс|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|ко̀чија|f}}\n*